    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Problem\n\n`gc` and `gcc` are not native mappings like `d` and `dd`, so one can't do this for example\n\n```vim\nnnoremap a gcc\n```\n\nSo one can't reuse `gc` and `gcc` for other purposes, as any mapping . They seem to be defined in `vim/_defaults.lua`\n\nIt would be nice, for the sake of consistency, if `gc` and `gcc` become first class citizens like `d`, `c`, etc.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n```vim\nnvim --clean\n:normal! gcc\n:noremap a gcc\na\n```\n\nnone of above works.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nI expect `:normal! gcc` to comment the current line.\nI also expect `a` after being defined as above, to comment the current line as well.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nv0.11.0-dev-4793+g21aed725d2-Homebrew\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nThis is not applicable to vim as far as I know\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nmacOS 15.3.1\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nGhostty 1.1\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-ghostty\n\n### Installation\n\nbrew install neovim -H",
